Proc.of Int.Workshop on Nuclear
Fission and Fission-product spectroscopy.
Fiss. fragm. mass yields for energies from 10 to 33 MeV
CYCLONE - Louvain-la-Neuve cyclotron
facility.
.The double kinetic energy method based on conservation
laws of mass and linear momentum was used to determine
fragment masses.
.Pre-neutron fragment masses and energies were
determined in an iterative procedure.
.Absolute energy calibration was done by using alpha
particles from Cf-252 source and a high precision
pulse generator.
.To subtract the wrap-around background, the fission
event time distributions were simulated by Monte-Carlo
folding of the neutron-induced fission cross-sections
of Th-232 from ENDF evaluated library and REL-REF of
P.W.Lisowski+ and of U-238 from ENDF evaluated
library and REL-REFs of A.D.Carlson with the neutron
spectrum of REL-REF H.Schuhmacher+ .
.Evaluation of REL-REF of A.C.Wahl was used to calcu-
late the mass distributions corresponding to the over-
lapping low energy neutrons.
Theoretical calculations and comparison
with experimental data
.Graphs for evaluated fission cross sections on Th-232
and U-238 are given
.For the grid inefficiency, detector pulse-height-
defect and fragment energy losses in the target
material, and for backing, for background.

as a fission fragment detector.
